        <!-- Section 6.1: Hypothesis Testing Framework -->
        <div class="section fade-in" id="framework">
            <h2 class="section-title">üéØ 6.1 Hypothesis Testing Framework</h2>
            <div class="section-content">
                <div class="hypothesis-framework">
                    <h4>Hypothesis Testing Setup</h4>
                    <p>A <strong>hypothesis test</strong> is a procedure for deciding between two competing claims about a population parameter.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Null Hypothesis ($H_0$):</strong> The claim being tested (status quo)</li>
                        <li><strong>Alternative Hypothesis ($H_1$ or $H_a$):</strong> The competing claim</li>
                        <li><strong>Test Statistic:</strong> Function of sample data used for decision</li>
                        <li><strong>Decision Rule:</strong> When to reject $H_0$</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="math-definition">
                    <h4>Types of Alternative Hypotheses</h4>
                    <table class="test-statistics-table">
                        <tr>
                            <th>Type</th>
                            <th>Null Hypothesis</th>
                            <th>Alternative Hypothesis</th>
                            <th>Example</th>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Two-sided</strong></td>
                            <td>$H_0: \theta = \theta_0$</td>
                            <td>$H_1: \theta \neq \theta_0$</td>
                            <td>$H_0: \mu = 100$ vs. $H_1: \mu \neq 100$</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Right-sided</strong></td>
                            <td>$H_0: \theta \leq \theta_0$</td>
                            <td>$H_1: \theta > \theta_0$</td>
                            <td>$H_0: \mu \leq 100$ vs. $H_1: \mu > 100$</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Left-sided</strong></td>
                            <td>$H_0: \theta \geq \theta_0$</td>
                            <td>$H_1: \theta < \theta_0$</td>
                            <td>$H_0: \mu \geq 100$ vs. $H_1: \mu < 100$</td>
                        </tr>
                    </table>
                </div>

                <div class="example-box">
                    <h4>Example 6.1: Quality Control</h4>
                    <p><strong>Scenario:</strong> A factory claims light bulbs last 1000 hours on average</p>
                    <p><strong>Hypotheses:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>$H_0: \mu = 1000$ (company's claim is true)</li>
                        <li>$H_1: \mu \neq 1000$ (claim is false)</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p><strong>Sample:</strong> Test $n = 36$ bulbs, observe $\bar{x} = 980$ hours</p>
                    <p><strong>Question:</strong> Is this evidence against the company's claim?</p>
                </div>

                <div class="theorem-box">
                    <h4>Decision Rule Framework</h4>
                    <ol>
                        <li><strong>Choose significance level:</strong> $\alpha$ (typically 0.05)</li>
                        <li><strong>Find critical region:</strong> Values of test statistic that lead to rejection</li>
                        <li><strong>Compute test statistic:</strong> From sample data</li>
                        <li><strong>Make decision:</strong> Reject $H_0$ if test statistic is in critical region</li>
                        <li><strong>Conclusion:</strong> State result in context of problem</li>
                    </ol>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Section 6.1 Practice -->
            <div class="section-practice">
