        <!-- Section 6.2: Type I and Type II Errors -->
        <div class="section fade-in" id="errors">
            <h2 class="section-title">‚ö†Ô∏è 6.2 Type I and Type II Errors</h2>
            <div class="section-content">
                <div class="error-types-box">
                    <h4>Types of Errors in Hypothesis Testing</h4>
                    <p>Since we make decisions based on sample data, <strong>errors are possible</strong>:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Type I Error:</strong> Reject $H_0$ when $H_0$ is true (False Positive)</li>
                        <li><strong>Type II Error:</strong> Fail to reject $H_0$ when $H_0$ is false (False Negative)</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="math-definition">
                    <h4>Decision Table</h4>
                    <table class="decision-table">
                        <tr>
                            <th rowspan="2" style="vertical-align: middle;"></th>
                            <th colspan="2">True State of Nature</th>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <th>$H_0$ True</th>
                            <th>$H_0$ False</th>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <th style="background: var(--primary-color); color: white;">Decision: Accept $H_0$</th>
                            <td class="correct">Correct Decision<br>Probability: $1 - \alpha$</td>
                            <td class="error">Type II Error<br>Probability: $\beta$</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <th style="background: var(--primary-color); color: white;">Decision: Reject $H_0$</th>
                            <td class="error">Type I Error<br>Probability: $\alpha$</td>
                            <td class="correct">Correct Decision<br>Probability: $1 - \beta$ (Power)</td>
                        </tr>
                    </table>
                </div>

                <div class="math-definition">
                    <h4>Error Probabilities</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Significance Level:</strong> $\alpha = P(\text{Type I Error}) = P(\text{Reject } H_0 | H_0 \text{ true})$</li>
                        <li><strong>Type II Error Probability:</strong> $\beta = P(\text{Type II Error}) = P(\text{Accept } H_0 | H_0 \text{ false})$</li>
                        <li><strong>Power:</strong> $1 - \beta = P(\text{Reject } H_0 | H_0 \text{ false})$</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="example-box">
                    <h4>Example 6.2: Medical Test</h4>
                    <p><strong>Scenario:</strong> Test for a disease</p>
                    <p><strong>Hypotheses:</strong> $H_0$: Patient is healthy, $H_1$: Patient has disease</p>
                    <p><strong>Type I Error:</strong> Healthy patient tests positive (False alarm)</p>
                    <p><strong>Type II Error:</strong> Diseased patient tests negative (Missed diagnosis)</p>
                    <p><strong>Trade-off:</strong> Reducing $\alpha$ typically increases $\beta$</p>
                </div>

                <div class="theorem-box">
                    <h4>Error Trade-offs</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Fixed sample size:</strong> Decreasing $\alpha$ usually increases $\beta$</li>
                        <li><strong>Increasing sample size:</strong> Can reduce both $\alpha$ and $\beta$</li>
                        <li><strong>Conventional choice:</strong> $\alpha = 0.05$ (5% significance level)</li>
                        <li><strong>Critical applications:</strong> May use $\alpha = 0.01$ or smaller</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

