        <!-- Section 6.4: p-values -->
        <div class="section fade-in" id="pvalues">
            <h2 class="section-title">üìä 6.4 p-values and Significance</h2>
            <div class="section-content">
                <div class="pvalue-box">
                    <h4>p-value Definition</h4>
                    <p>The <strong>p-value</strong> is the probability of observing a test statistic as extreme or more extreme than what was observed, assuming $H_0$ is true.</p>
                    <div class="math-formula">
                        $p\text{-value} = P(T \geq t_{obs} | H_0 \text{ true})$ (for right-tailed test)
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Decision Rule:</strong> Reject $H_0$ if p-value $\leq \alpha$</p>
                </div>

                <div class="math-definition">
                    <h4>p-value Calculations</h4>
                    <table class="test-statistics-table">
                        <tr>
                            <th>Test Type</th>
                            <th>Alternative</th>
                            <th>p-value</th>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Two-tailed</td>
                            <td>$H_1: \theta \neq \theta_0$</td>
                            <td>$2P(T \geq |t_{obs}|)$</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Right-tailed</td>
                            <td>$H_1: \theta > \theta_0$</td>
                            <td>$P(T \geq t_{obs})$</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Left-tailed</td>
                            <td>$H_1: \theta < \theta_0$</td>
                            <td>$P(T \leq t_{obs})$</td>
                        </tr>
                    </table>
                </div>

                <div class="example-box">
                    <h4>Example 6.4: p-value Calculation</h4>
                    <p><strong>Test:</strong> $H_0: \mu = 100$ vs. $H_1: \mu \neq 100$</p>
                    <p><strong>Sample:</strong> $n = 25$, $\bar{x} = 105$, $s = 10$</p>
                    <p><strong>Test Statistic:</strong> $t = \frac{105 - 100}{10/\sqrt{25}} = \frac{5}{2} = 2.5$</p>
                    <p><strong>Distribution:</strong> $t_{24}$ (24 degrees of freedom)</p>
                    <p><strong>p-value:</strong> $2P(T_{24} \geq 2.5) \approx 2(0.0098) = 0.0196$</p>
                    <p><strong>Conclusion:</strong> Reject $H_0$ at $\alpha = 0.05$ since p-value < 0.05</p>
                </div>

                <div class="theorem-box">
                    <h4>p-value Interpretation</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Small p-value (‚â§ Œ±):</strong> Strong evidence against $H_0$, reject $H_0$</li>
                        <li><strong>Large p-value (> Œ±):</strong> Insufficient evidence against $H_0$, fail to reject $H_0$</li>
                        <li><strong>Common cutoffs:</strong> 0.05, 0.01, 0.10</li>
                        <li><strong>Strength of evidence:</strong>
                            <ul>
                                <li>p < 0.01: Very strong evidence</li>
                                <li>0.01 ‚â§ p < 0.05: Strong evidence</li>
                                <li>0.05 ‚â§ p < 0.10: Moderate evidence</li>
                                <li>p ‚â• 0.10: Little to no evidence</li>
                            </ul>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

