        <!-- Section 6.6: Likelihood Ratio Tests -->
        <div class="section fade-in" id="likelihood-ratio">
            <h2 class="section-title">üìà 6.6 Likelihood Ratio Tests</h2>
            <div class="section-content">
                <div class="math-definition">
                    <h4>Likelihood Ratio Test (LRT)</h4>
                    <p>The <strong>likelihood ratio test</strong> is a general method for constructing hypothesis tests.</p>
                    <div class="math-formula">
                        $\Lambda = \frac{\max_{\theta \in \Theta_0} L(\theta)}{\max_{\theta \in \Theta} L(\theta)} = \frac{L(\hat{\theta}_0)}{L(\hat{\theta})}$
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Decision Rule:</strong> Reject $H_0$ if $\Lambda \leq c$ for some critical value $c$</p>
                </div>

                <div class="theorem-box">
                    <h4>Wilks' Theorem</h4>
                    <p>Under regularity conditions, as $n \to \infty$:</p>
                    <div class="math-formula">
                        $-2 \ln \Lambda \xrightarrow{d} \chi^2_k$
                    </div>
                    <p>where $k$ = difference in number of parameters between $H_1$ and $H_0$</p>
                </div>

                <div class="example-box">
                    <h4>Example 6.6: Normal Mean LRT</h4>
                    <p><strong>Test:</strong> $H_0: \mu = \mu_0$ vs. $H_1: \mu \neq \mu_0$ (œÉ¬≤ known)</p>
                    <p><strong>LR Statistic:</strong> $\Lambda = \exp\left(-\frac{n(\bar{x} - \mu_0)^2}{2\sigma^2}\right)$</p>
                    <p><strong>Equivalent to:</strong> Rejecting when $|\bar{x} - \mu_0|$ is large</p>
                    <p><strong>Result:</strong> LRT gives the same test as the z-test</p>
                </div>

                <div class="theorem-box">
                    <h4>LRT Properties</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>General framework:</strong> Works for any parametric model</li>
                        <li><strong>Optimal properties:</strong> Most powerful under certain conditions</li>
                        <li><strong>Asymptotic distribution:</strong> Chi-square under $H_0$</li>
                        <li><strong>Connection to MLEs:</strong> Based on maximum likelihood estimation</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <!-- Section 6.6 Practice -->
                <div class="section-practice">
                    <h3 style="color: var(--primary-color); margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">üìà Section 6.6 Practice</h3>
                    
