                correctAnswers: ["null hypothesis", "null", "status quo", "claim being tested"],
                hint: "Think about what we're testing against",
                explanation: "H‚ÇÄ represents the null hypothesis - the claim being tested or the status quo that we're trying to find evidence against.",
                steps: `<div class="step-title">Hypothesis Testing Setup:</div>
                        <div class="step-content">
                            <ol>
                                <li><strong>H‚ÇÄ:</strong> Null hypothesis (claim being tested)</li>
                                <li><strong>H‚ÇÅ:</strong> Alternative hypothesis (competing claim)</li>
                                <li><strong>Goal:</strong> Decide which hypothesis is supported by data</li>
                                <li><strong>Default:</strong> Assume H‚ÇÄ is true unless strong evidence against it</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>`
            },
            {
                question: "For testing H‚ÇÄ: Œº = 100 vs H‚ÇÅ: Œº ‚â† 100, what type of test is this?",
                correctAnswers: ["two-sided", "two-tailed", "two sided", "two tailed"],
                hint: "Look at the alternative hypothesis - does it specify a direction?",
                explanation: "This is a two-sided (or two-tailed) test because the alternative hypothesis H‚ÇÅ: Œº ‚â† 100 doesn't specify a particular direction - Œº could be either greater than or less than 100.",
                steps: `<div class="step-title">Test Types:</div>
                        <div class="step-content">
                            <ol>
                                <li><strong>Two-sided:</strong> H‚ÇÅ: Œ∏ ‚â† Œ∏‚ÇÄ (parameter can be above or below)</li>
                                <li><strong>Right-sided:</strong> H‚ÇÅ: Œ∏ > Œ∏‚ÇÄ (parameter is greater than)</li>
                                <li><strong>Left-sided:</strong> H‚ÇÅ: Œ∏ < Œ∏‚ÇÄ (parameter is less than)</li>
                                <li><strong>Our case:</strong> Œº ‚â† 100 ‚Üí two-sided test</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>`
            },
            {
                question: "What is the first step in conducting a hypothesis test?",
                correctAnswers: ["state hypotheses", "set up hypotheses", "choose significance level", "formulate hypotheses"],
                hint: "What do you need to establish before collecting data?",
                explanation: "The first step is to clearly state the null and alternative hypotheses that you want to test.",
                steps: `<div class="step-title">Hypothesis Testing Steps:</div>
                        <div class="step-content">
                            <ol>
                                <li><strong>Step 1:</strong> State H‚ÇÄ and H‚ÇÅ clearly</li>
                                <li><strong>Step 2:</strong> Choose significance level Œ±</li>
